# Touchscreen-first / kiosk UX (Chore Wheel)

Chore Wheel is used on a **wall- or fridge-mounted touch display**. Assume **no keyboard** for day-to-day use. Keyboard, precise pointing, and dense layouts are acceptable **only on setup/admin surfaces**, and those surfaces should still remain touch-usable.

## Touch targets and layout

- Aim for **at least ~44×44 CSS px** per interactive control (including icon-only buttons). Add padding to small visuals so the hit area meets this, not just the glyph.
- Leave **clear space between** tappable controls to reduce mis-taps. Avoid tight clusters on primary flows.
- Prefer **large, full-width, or pill-shaped** actions on the main wheel / chore flow.

## Hover, state, and feedback

- Do **not** rely on `:hover` for essential labels, actions, or state. Use always-visible text/icons; use hover as enhancement only.
- Provide obvious **active/pressed** feedback for touch (`active:` in Tailwind, or equivalent). Loading/disabled states must be visible without hovering.

## Typography and content

- **Body text** on primary screens: **at least 16px**. Scale headings and CTAs for **arm’s-length** reading.
- Keep the main wheel screen **scannable**; avoid long paragraphs there.

## Scrolling and gestures

- Use **clear scroll regions** when content overflows; avoid layouts where users cannot tell what scrolls.
- Avoid accidental horizontal drift on vertically scrolled lists unless horizontal swipe is intentional—if you add swipe gestures, document them in code/comments.

## Tailwind / CSS patterns

- Encode minimum size with **`min-h-*` / `min-w-*`** plus padding on the interactive wrapper, not only on inner text.
- On buttons and primary links, prefer **`touch-manipulation`** (e.g. Tailwind `touch-manipulation`) where double-tap zoom causes jank on kiosk browsers.

### Example (hit area)

```tsx
// BAD — icon may look big but tap target is too small
<button type="button" className="p-0">
  <Icon className="size-5" />
</button>

// GOOD — minimum touch target with comfortable padding
<button
  type="button"
  className="inline-flex min-h-11 min-w-11 touch-manipulation items-center justify-center rounded-full p-3 active:opacity-80"
  aria-label="Spin wheel"
>
  <Icon className="size-6" />
</button>
```

## Keyboard and shortcuts

- **Core chore/wheel actions** must not require keyboard shortcuts, precise Tab order, or mouse-only interactions.
- Shortcuts on **admin** routes are fine if documented; when focus is possible, keep **visible focus** styles for accessibility.

## Forms (setup / admin)

- Use **large inputs**, appropriate **`type`** / **`inputMode`**, and tap-friendly controls (native pickers where suitable).
- Avoid **dense tables** on touch-first paths; if tables are admin-only, keep rows/cells touch-friendly.

## Viewport and zoom

- **Pinch-zoom off** can stabilize kiosk UIs but **reduces accessibility**—if you constrain scaling, document the choice in code/comments and prefer touch-friendly sizing instead of relying on zoom.
